cs.DL, cs.IR, cs.SI, cs.DB, cs.CY 

The paper proposes a novel data structure to model the organization of follow-up papers and their dependencies through citations, and derives metrics to quantify the influence of a paper. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of computer science that deal with bibliometrics, information retrieval, data structures, and databases. Specifically, cs.DL (Digital Libraries) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are the most likely sub-categories as they deal directly with bibliometrics and citation analysis. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.DB (Databases) are also likely as they deal with data structures and dependencies. Finally, cs.CY (Computers and Society) is a less likely sub-category, but it is possible that the paper discusses the societal impact of scientific papers.
